        <p>Have you ever wondered if the birds flying in the sky are truly free of burden? Is that why they were able to
            fly so lightly? The winds accommodate them because of their shared freedom, fluttering and moving, to reach
            everything.</p>
        <p>I am envious of them.</p>
        <p>I barely see the birds through the window, blotted with water from the rain that is pouring. I can barely see
            the surroundings even when I'm squinting, and I'm sitting in the passenger seat of a car. It was a big car,
            family-sized, almost felt like a minivan.</p>
        <p>Do not quote me on that, though. I am very bad with cars and such; my comparison tends to be very wrong
            because of it.</p>
        <p>I see my father in the driver's seat and loads of stuff in the back of the car, including one small
            motorcycle being tied down by a plastic rope.</p>
        <p>I remember this scene, this memory, but I don't remember the rain. I was sleep deprived at the time, very
            worried that my dad would also fall asleep if I slept myself, and focused on keeping him awake.</p>
        <p>By talking to him about everything.</p>
        <p>It was the first time I've ever had such an open discussion with the man I've decided to hate so much. It was
            also one of the good memories I've had of him in recent times.</p>
        <p>I looked at him and said, "Dad?"</p>
        <p>Surprisingly, he answered, "Yeah, bud?"</p>
        <p>Shaking off my surprise, I decided to continue and see what would happen. "Have you ever heard the tale of
            the two birds?"</p>
        <p>"Two birds? Kid, I've lost count of how many stories you've told me. How about you start the story and see if
            it jogs my memory a bit?" He said, eyes focusing still on the road. He has always been different when he is
            driving. Focused and his energy never seems to diminish.</p>
        <p>"Okay then..." I said, recounting the words to the tale. "It was said that two birds used to live a long time
            ago, a parent and a child. There were many variations on which parent or child it was, father and daughter.
            Father and son. Mother and son, and rarely, mother and daughter."</p>
        <p>I almost rambled on and on about the intriguing fact of the story, but realized that I'm digressing from the
            topic. "Anyway, for the moment, let's assume it was the variation of father and son," I said shamelessly.
        </p>
        <p>I saw my father raise his eyebrows and take a slight look at me, but he didn't reply.</p>
        <p>"The father bird and its son used to live together with a mother. A bird that dotes on both of them as a
            lover and a parent. The mother bird is the one thing that binds them together, a common ground that they
            both love her. In a mature way, or in a childlike way. Either way, they have that to tie them together."</p>
        <p>The silence between us was interspersed with the sound of the beating rain, creating this thick, tense
            atmosphere. The air seems to be charged with static energy.</p>
        <p>"One day, the mother bird was struck with an illness. Her chirping became solemn and slow, and later on, she
            was too weak to even fly. The father worked tirelessly to feed her, hunting for worms and bringing them as
            fast as he could. The son was too young to help the father in hunting for food, but he helped the mother
            bird around the nest whenever she needed to do something."</p>
        <p>I take a peek at my father and see his hand tightening on the steering wheel, and his barely contained
            emotion. I forged on, hoping not to get choked up before the story ends.</p>
        <p>"But in the end, they were helpless, and they were both together when the mother bird was at her weakest
            point. The mother bird did not have a long time to live. The mother bird chirps to the father bird, crying,
            saying 'Thank you for everything, dear. I&hellip; am sorry I have to go first. I am glad that we both
            decided to fly together.'" I said, delivering it without losing myself.</p>
        <p>"The mother bird then turned to the son and said, 'Be strong, son. Keep flapping your wings. I'm sorry I
            can't live to see you fly, but I know you will. Don't let anyone and anything bring you down, okay? Fly, fly
            away, be free.' And with those last words, she chirps a little bit and closes her eyes. Her feather loses
            its luster, now attached to something without its soul." I finally dropped a tear, unable to contain my own
            sadness that had been silently welling up, but I continued.</p>
        <p>"The birds, father and son, then worked together to bury the mother bird, and after they were done, they
            talked with each other in a hollowed-out tree," I said, looking away from the driver of this car. This part
            is the hardest.</p>
        <p>"The father started the talk by asking the son to stay inside, to keep himself safe, and to never fly at all.
            The son, remembering the last words of his mother, protested and argued, but the father wouldn't budge. He
            then said, 'I cannot lose anyone again, do you understand?'" I said, steeling myself.</p>
        <p>I am not courageous enough to see his reaction, and I don't want to.</p>
        <p>"The son, however, began to pull on his wing in protest; he wants to be free, as his mother wanted. He
            struggled and struggled until the father responded, out of instinct. He pushed away his son, towards a hole
            in the hollowed-out tree. An accident." I said, solemnly. "He realized what he had done and flew away,
            losing a bit of himself as the winds beat up against him. The son, betrayed, fell to the inside of the tree
            and broke his wings. His father has left him here to die, in his misguided attempt to keep him safe. His
            grief has let him-"</p>
        <p>I wasn't able to finish my story before my father slammed his hand to the steering wheel, screaming, "Stop
            it! Just stop! I understand the point, okay?!" as he let out the rage I knew he always had, inherited from
            his father.</p>
        <p>The one I also unfortunately inherited.</p>
        <p>The silence hangs like a lampshade, illuminating my intentions while its shadow covered the rage of my
            father, as he attempted to calm himself down. Neither of us breaks it, stewing in our own minds. The storm
            outside only complemented the brewing storm of emotions that was about to break at any moment now.</p>
        <p>I looked ahead to see if I could still see the birds. In the rain, I can see it still fluttering its wings,
            hopefully looking for a warmer, and less wet, place. I focus on the birds still, thinking of their freedom,
            and making sure I do not get caught up in too many emotions.</p>
        <p>It's just memories, nothing more. There's no need to be afraid.</p>
        <p>After a while of driving through the endless roads, we finally reach a change of scenery. The car starts to
            climb up as we ride through an overpass, and the rain starts to dissipate. I can now clearly see the birds
            and see how static its animation was, then I focus my attention on my dad.</p>
        <p>This is the moment, the reason why I'm here in the first place.</p>
        <p>"Did you really feel like that?" I hear him say, his voice trembling as if a million thunderstorms are
            vibrating his mouth. "Like I betrayed you?"</p>
        <p>"Dad, I was just telling a story. It does not have anything to do with our&hellip; situation." I give my
            response, barely straining to contain my emotion. I want to scream at him, agreeing and giving him a rude
            awakening, about how I actually feel.</p>
        <p>"Are you sure?" Dad said. His eyes looked at me for a second, and I could see some of the gentleness that
            must've charmed my mother in his eyes. For a mere second, I believe this man genuinely cared about my
            well-being.</p>
        <p>I looked back at him, defiant, "Don't look at me like that." I spoke with less control over my anger. I
            remember the exact word I said to him. "Don't pretend like you care!" I yelled and let everything out as I
            said the last word.</p>
        <p>"You don't! You never do, ever since she's gone! You're only interested in keeping me safe, never letting me
            out, limiting my freedom, you take everything from me!" I said, not even caring if it's the same line or
            not. "You even drove away-"</p>
        <p>"No! You can curse me for doing everything else, but you cannot fault me for breaking that one up. She was
            about to kidnap you!" At this moment, he had lost all focus on the road and looked at me incredulously.</p>
        <p>"We were only going for a week, why can't you trust that your almost adult son is capable of going overseas
            without being in danger?" I said, rebutting his point.</p>
        <p>And it continues. The argument flooded out, and we let out everything that we have kept in since Mom is gone.
            We argued until our throats couldn't produce any more sounds, and even then, we continued. At one point, I
            looked at the birds and focused on them, and I saw the whole world melting away.</p>
        <p><img src="/assets/icons/Birds.svg" alt="Birds icon" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"
                width="40px" class="filter"></p>
        <p>"Status check on the subject."</p>
        <p>"Subject is still in a healthy condition. Their vitals are slightly abnormal, but this is to be expected as
            we explore the most vulnerable parts of his brain. So far, it's going great. The indicator worked perfectly
