        <p>"Is it safe to continue?"</p>
        <p>"At this point, it is still safe. No danger can be detected from the parameter that was given."</p>
        <p>"Initiate stage two."</p>
        <p>"Stage two commencing. Calibrating pulses, constructing worlds&hellip;"</p>
        <p><img src="/assets/icons/Birds.svg" alt="Birds icon" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"
                width="40px" class="filter"></p>
        <p>I finally regained my senses after the world melted away, and I felt the softness and the warmth. I am in a
            bed, without my clothes on, and apparently with someone else. I recognized the person immediately, and I
            hadn't opened my eyes yet. I do, however, move my hand to pat their long black hair, which was tickling my
            body with its volume.</p>
        <p>I heard a groan and felt the lady hug me tight. It seems like I'm not the only one who has woken up.</p>
        <p>"Good morning," I said, still with eyes closed and with a tired voice. The thing about feeling memory as an
            Agent is, you feel everything, including how groggy they must've felt waking up in the morning, so I played
            the part. "You can let go now, you're hugging me like I'm going to be taken away at any moment," I said,
            chuckling.</p>
        <p>I can only hear grunts as a response. Okay, she might not be as awake as indicated; it's just a natural
            response. That is kind of cute.</p>
        <p>I shake myself awake and distance myself from the emotion. I am an Agent, not whoever this person is. I have
            to remember that, and so I opened my eyes. I looked at the ceiling and saw the painting of two birds in a
            nest, nuzzling with each other. I can recall that this painting was specifically made by the person who is
            currently nuzzling me right now, and she painted it as a present for our anniversary.</p>
        <p>Very unusual, but this subject is an unusual person, so I let it slide.</p>
        <p>I was about to rise before I could feel her movement. I looked at her, and I saw that she was finally awake,
            her big eyes looking at me like a child caught with its hand on the cookie jar. I looked back and tilted my
            head. She ducked down and started moving her body.</p>
        <p>Oh, she wants that. Well&hellip;.</p>
        <p>I indulged in her needs. There's nothing left to be said. If this is what I need to do to gain knowledge,
            I'll do it.</p>
        <p>I also won't lie, even if it's only a memory of another person, it still felt good.</p>
        <p>As I lay back together with her, I looked again at the birds. But soon my vision is penetrated by tangles of
            black hair and the beautiful face of a lady. "Good morning, indeed." She smirked. I pinched her cheek in
            response, as I felt it was appropriate, and she lay on my chest.</p>
        <p>We lay there for a bit before she started piping up. "I'm glad you know."</p>
        <p>"Glad for what?"</p>
        <p>"I'm glad that you fought to be with me, <em>shshshsh</em>." I heard her say, but the last part was blurred.
            The privacy protocol is working great. I can't tell what she said, but I can infer it is the subject's real
            name.</p>
        <p>I looked away in embarrassment before shaking myself from that and looking towards her. I can't let the
            subject's emotion overtake my own. "You're worth fighting for, Ali."</p>
        <p>The lady, Ali, looked at me with what I can only describe as loving eyes. "Yeah, so please excuse me when I
            hugged you really tight, because I don't want you to go anywhere." She said, then she began hugging me tight
            again.</p>
        <p>Ah, this memory. It finally caught up to me. The subject and his girlfriend, Ali, are about to embark on a
            long-distance relationship. The subject has to move for a period of time because of his work, which I'm
            investigating. Ali is very adamant that they spend a night with each other before he goes, which was last
            night.</p>
        <p>I didn't say anything. What else can I say? I feel like the subject wouldn't say anything at this moment
            either, just enjoying it before he inevitably has to go and fly away, towards the freedom unknown.</p>
        <p>I let myself pat her on the back and softly caress it as well while I look at the birds.</p>
        <p>I find myself envious of them again, as the love they exude from the painting, nuzzling with each other, was
            so palpable. I want to be like them, stay here nuzzling Ali forever, just like them.</p>
        <p>What am I even thinking? She's not mine, I'm not even sure she's still alive. I mentally slap my own cheeks.
            The more I delve into the subject's mind, the more of his feelings and thoughts leak out. I have to be in
            control.</p>
        <p>But wouldn't it be nice if I stayed here with Ali, even for one more minute?</p>
        <p>I sighed in frustration and decided to ask her a question to distract myself and possibly gain more answers.
            "I wish I could stay too, forever if possible," I said, with a somber tone to disguise the earlier sigh as
            something sad.</p>
        <p>I waited for a response, but I could only feel her embrace. I look at her, wondering if she fell asleep,
            before I start to feel something wet touching my skin, coming from the area of her face. Oh, tears.</p>
        <p>I quickly said, "Hey, hey, are you okay?" while I pulled her up to face me. She began sobbing as soon as she
            left the embrace, and I said, "It's not going to be long, okay? I'll be back before you can even miss me."
        </p>
        <p>She didn't say anything at first and kept sobbing, but at some point, she looked at me with watery eyes.
            "Promise me you'll contact me every night?"</p>
        <p>"Promise."</p>
        <p>"Promise me you won't find anyone else there?"</p>
        <p>He smirked. "You know that all my mates are going to be guys, right?"</p>
        <p>"I don't know, maybe you'll decide to swing the other way or something."</p>
        <p>I coughed and pinched her cheek with both of my hands. She can be a little bit paranoid at times, and I find
            it cute. "I assure you, I only think of you when I'm thinking of a partner, or relationship-wise. So don't
            worry too much about that."</p>
        <p>"Owkway," she said while I kept pinching her cheeks. She smiled a bit as she said that.</p>
        <p>I stopped and faced her up close, smirking and said, "Anything else you're worried about?"</p>
        <p>She slapped my face away lightly and said, "I still can't tell what job you're going to do there." She looked
            at me inquisitively. I recall that she always asked me about this as the due date is coming close. "Can you
            at least tell me one inconsequential detail about it?"</p>
        <p>I shook my head and said, "You know I can't." I mentally cursed, because the reason I can't answer it is that
            the subject doesn't let me remember. "Confidentiality and all that," I said, trying to excuse myself while
            hoping that I could finally recall the memory.</p>
        <p>"Please, just one for me?" She said, doing that puppy eyes move that she did previously. I looked at her, and
            a burst of emotion came forth. The subject is really in love with this girl, Ali, it seems.</p>
        <p>And I feel myself falling for her as well. I shook my head a bit, and she must've taken that as a definitive
            answer to her question, because she began to sulk and pulled away from me.</p>
        <p>I looked at her and felt guilty. At this point, I wasn't sure if this was the subject's feeling at the time
            or my own; it coalesces together into a mix of both, our shared collective guilt as we have to tell her
            basically nothing.</p>
        <p>As we struggle with it, and possibly after the subject takes time to reconsider, I was able to recall a
            memory, something that I can use as an answer. Something that the subject has been thinking about for a
            while, actually.</p>
        <p>"I can tell you at least that what I'm working for&hellip; has been made into a movie once."</p>
        <p>Ali looked back, her sulking over, and looked at me incredulously. "Wait, what?"</p>
        <p>I unconsciously scratch my hair in embarrassment and look elsewhere to stop being embarrassed. "Yeah, that's
            all I can tell you." I glanced at her a bit before saying, "Is that enough?"</p>
        <p>She grinned, the widest grin I've ever seen coming from her, I mean, coming from any girl. "That is the first
            time I've heard you open up about the job." She goes back to hugging me tightly again. "It's not enough, but
            I take what I can get."</p>
        <p>I hugged her back and smiled warmly. "Sorry that I can't give you more."</p>
        <p>We sat there forever, warm skin and our beating heart together for what could have been the last time.
            Hopefully not.</p>
        <p>"Don't you have to go in a few hours? You know the roads to the airport at these hours, it's busy." She said,
            finally, looking up to me.</p>
        <p>"Just a couple more minutes," I said, looking at her. "Or do you want me to leave?"</p>
        <p>"No." She said, and she came close for a kiss, but the whole world melted away before I could feel the soft
            lips.</p>
