        <p>My head exploded. Or at least it felt like it. Information is being streamed directly to my brain as I start
            to regain my senses, and I see a laboratory. Machines that I barely recognized, before my memories caught up
            with me and I began to understand their purposes. People are working on their own machine, unrecognizable
            faces, slowly became familiar as I learn the context.</p>
        <p>I learn alright, I learn to lean on my own desk, and I almost doubled over in pain.</p>
        <p>One of the subject's colleagues noticed my movements and walked over, saying, "You okay, man?"</p>
        <p>I put my hand up to say I'm okay and shook my head. So much information, the information that might be useful
            for the mission. "Haven't drunk my coffee yet."</p>
        <p>"Ah." He said, with an understanding look. "You want me to get you one? There's a recent pot that was being
            brewed over in the kitchen."</p>
        <p>"Oh, I don't want to take your time."</p>
        <p>"Nah, don't worry. I also need some refills on my own." He said with a knowing look. "It's crunch time
            anyway." He then walked away, towards presumably the kitchen.</p>
        <p>I took my time to pinch the side of my head to alleviate the lingering pain that was slowly subsiding, and
            take a look at the laboratory. It was packed with both men and machines, working in tandem to create&hellip;
            something. A contraption, but to do what? The subject's memories are scattered, but I know the answer is in
            here somewhere.</p>
        <p>I look at my desk and take a gander at my notes, filled with calculations and plans for parts of the
            contraption. There is also a symbol of a bird on the bottom left of the paper, which seems like it is a
            custom-made paper specifically for this lab. I focused on the bird, the indicator for this memory, it seems,
            but I can't reach the same feeling as the previous memories.</p>
        <p>I looked at the symbol still, and I almost gasped in surprise as it turned fuzzy, like the image turns into a
            lower resolution version of itself. I rubbed my eyes, and it turned back into a normal bird logo. I sat
            there and got a grip on myself.</p>
        <p>I am not the subject. I am an Agent.</p>
        <p>I am not the subject. I am an Agent.</p>
        <p>I am not the&hellip; subject. Or am I?</p>
        <p>I shook my head and decided to look at my notes, to decipher the calculations and retain the information and
            memories for the folks out there to receive, along with following the inclinations of the subject.</p>
        <p>I missed the fact that I started following the subject's intentions in his memories and the implication when
            I was tapped on the shoulder. I looked back and saw the same scientist colleague, carrying two mugs of
            steaming hot coffee.</p>
        <p>"Here you go." He handed over one of the mugs.</p>
        <p>I took it and said, "Thanks." I carefully put it in the available room on the desk, filled with clutter of
            parts and notes.</p>
        <p>The scientists looked at the notes I'm reading and said, "Recalculating the variables?"</p>
        <p>"Yeah, I calculated this when I'm tired, want to make sure that I didn't miscalculate."</p>
        <p>He grimaced before saying, "Oof, good luck then, man." He patted my shoulder before returning to his station.
        </p>
        <p>"You too&hellip;" I started recalling his name and job station, "Pat. Did you have a good time with the
            programs?"</p>
        <p>"Oh, yeah. I've finished the interface; it should be able to respond dynamically soon, but as of right now,
            it can respond to base questions and information. You want to see?" Pat said, gesturing to his monitor.</p>
        <p>"Yeah, what the hell." I stood up and walked towards his station. "Maybe seeing progress can help me
            calculate better. Motivations and all."</p>
        <p>"Uh-uh." Pat sat on his chair, and typed some things, saying, "A few kinks that I just noticed, let me fix
            that real quick&hellip; Some of these missed the debugger, you know? Cause technically, it's true, but the
            calculations will be wrong in the long run." He's still typing and did an impromptu bug fixing while
            talking, and I looked at the program.</p>
        <p>All the information here, I need to retain to peruse later. I looked at it thoroughly and pointed out
            something to him. "Missed a semicolon here."</p>
        <p>Pat snickered. "Years into this job, I still miss that here and there." He typed the semicolon in before
            continuing to bug-fix the program. "Sorry about this, I was ready to showcase that for my own ego, but I
            just realized the mistake, so give me a few more seconds&hellip;"</p>
        <p>He typed a few last lines of code. "Done!" Pat exclaimed. No error on the debugger, nor from my own perusal.
        </p>
        <p>I looked at him and gave him a thumbs-up. "Showcase?"</p>
        <p>"Showcase." He said, and he clicked the running option.</p>
        <p>I see a simple text input UI, presumably to enter a command. He put in a simple command, &lsquo;Subject
            status check.'</p>
        <p>"I haven't hooked it up to any subject yet, so it would automatically respond with the ideal condition of a
            subject." He said, explaining the program. This program would be used to interface with our subject on the
            contraption, monitoring their vitals. I see the response.</p>
        <p>"Subject is in healthy condition."</p>
        <p>Pat continues, "The program would dynamically respond according to the subject's actual vitals at the moment
            we used it. Some peculiar vitals that spike at certain moments or drop suddenly. I made progress on that,
            but I still don't have anything to show for it, especially because I do need some live data to showcase that
            feature, so this is the best I can do for now. What do you think?"</p>
        <p>I pondered for a moment before saying, "It's basic, but progress. Better than nothing." I continued. "You'd
            better work on that dynamic response, though. I heard that the bosses are looking to test this soon."</p>
        <p>"You don't have to remind me." He said grumpily and slowly sipped on his coffee.</p>
        <p>"Let me know when you're done. I want to see that final version."</p>
        <p>Pat beamed and said, "For sure, <em>shshsh.</em> I'll let you know!" Pat then began furiously working on the
            program, periodically drinking his coffee.</p>
        <p>I return to my station and start doing my job as well. I looked at the notes and made some calculations.
            After a few minutes, I tried to find my pen, looking around my desk before opening the drawer. I saw two
            small face-down picture frames in the clutter inside the drawer. Curious, I turned them up and saw the
            picture of my own, a family of three. My dad, my mom, and I. The other one contained the picture of me and
            Ali.</p>
        <p>Why were these in a drawer again? I tried to remember, and I recalled the answer.</p>
        <p>Ali and I were having difficulties with our relationship, and last night she called me and asked me to take a
            break from our relationship. I shelved her pictures then, because I can't see her while I'm working. I can't
            afford to see her static image and ponder on the future of our relationship while I still have a job to do.
        </p>
        <p>My family's pictures have always been shelved; I can't bear seeing them on my desk, but I can't just throw
            them away either.</p>
        <p>No wonder I was worried that my calculations were wrong. Wait, me or the subject?</p>
        <p>I am the subject- no, I'm the Agent.</p>
        <p>I am the Agent.</p>
        <p>Why does that sound so&hellip; wrong?</p>
        <p><img src="/assets/icons/Birds.svg" alt="Birds icon" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"
                width="40px" class="filter"></p>
        <p>"Status check on the subject."</p>
        <p>"Vitals are dropping as we extracted information from him. It is expected, but the level of the vitals is
            approaching a new low. The data of this has been collected for future consideration."</p>
        <p>"Status check on the agent."</p>
        <p>"Agent is&hellip; Agent is&hellip;"</p>
        <p>"Status check on the agent."</p>
        <p>"Return 122502348&hellip;"</p>
        <p class="monospace">RELOAD BIRDSinterface.exe</p>
        <p>"Status check on the subject."</p>
        <p>"Subjects are in healthy condition."</p>
        <p>"Status check on the agent."</p>
        <p>"There is no Agent detected."</p>
        <p><img src="/assets/icons/Birds.svg" alt="Birds icon" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;"
                width="40px" class="filter"></p>
        <p>I no longer feel envious of the birds.</p>
        <p>I feel like the winds have finally accommodated me now. Like a wing grew out of my back, I feel so light.</p>
        <p>I keep on working on the calculation, and hope that I can finish&nbsp;it before the end of the day. Before
            that happens, though, the bosses came from the back of the laboratory. Inspection time, it seems.</p>
        <p>We lined up at our stations, awaiting the bosses as they inspected our work and asked questions. They never
            seem to approach my desk, though, probably because they trust my calculation, and also the mathematics are
            probably beyond them.</p>
        <p>They finished their inspection and finally retreated. We were ready to return to our job before we heard a
            sharp throat clearing from one of them.</p>
        <p>Our attention returns to them, but not without some having a quizzical look on their faces. This never
            happened before. Is this some kind of announcement?</p>
        <p>"We have an announcement to make. During your induction to the project, we mentioned that this project
            remains nameless for the time being while it is being ruminated over. We are now announcing that the names
            of the project have been decided, and hopefully, with this, it would spur your motivation for the completion
            of a project, while before it might have&nbsp;an unfinished and rushed feeling to it," said one of the
            bosses.</p>
        <p>We never really learned their names, even though we've been here for a long time. With the amount of money
            that was being paid to us, we feel like they have a reason not to introduce themselves.</p>
        <p>It would also allow us to claim ignorance if this whole operation is being shut down at the behest of the
            government and we're being interrogated. At least some of us are thinking like that.</p>
        <p>"We have decided to name the project Project Birds."</p>
        <p>I felt a sudden urge to throw up. What did he say?</p>
        <p>"The leadership of this project has congregated and approved of the name, as we feel like it lines up with
            the goal of our project, which was to&hellip;"</p>
        <p>I can't hear what he has to say next, because I feel like I have just listened to something important. The
            importance of it somehow kept slipping from my brain, though. It does feel like it's on the tip of my
            tongue, however.</p>
        <p>I pinched my sides for a bit to focus and start listening back to the explanation.</p>
        <p>"With that concluded, we hope that this announcement renews your passion for the project and adds more
            motivation to complete it in a thorough and timely manner. Thank you." The bosses then turned around and
            exited the premises.</p>
        <p>Project Birds. Why is that name so familiar to me?</p>
        <p>I pondered and pondered, but I never found the answer. I then return to the job I've always had, calculating
            these formulas and variables.</p>
        <p>I hope that Ali will talk to me again. I also still need to contact my father. If what Pat says is right, it
            might not be too late.</p>
        <p>I have to let go of this burden of guilt. I know Mom would hope that I do. It's time to be free and not let
            this bring me down.</p>
